# Git & Pipeline Conventions

## Branching

- Feature branches: `feature/<name>`
- Hotfix branches: `hotfix/<issue-id>`
- Refactor branches: `refactor/<area>`
- Test branches: `test/<scope>`

## Commits

Use conventional commit format:
- `feat: <description>` — new feature
- `fix: <description>` — bug fix
- `refactor: <description>` — code improvement
- `test: <description>` — test additions/changes
- `docs: <description>` — documentation
- `chore: <description>` — maintenance

One logical change per commit. Atomic commits only.

## Rules

- Never force-push to main
- Feature branches for all development
- Keep main branch always deployable
- PR descriptions include: summary, changes, test results
- Clean git state after every pipeline operation (no uncommitted changes, no unresolved conflicts)

## Post-Pipeline Validation

After any git operations, verify:
1. `git status` is clean — no uncommitted changes
2. No failed pushes or unresolved merge conflicts
3. Current branch is in a consistent state
